# Numerical discrepancy pitfalls — load at write time, not just review time

Authoritative source: `.ai/skills/model-integration/pitfalls.md`
— the 12-item catalog of things that have made a diffusers port's outputs diverge from the reference. It is a
**consult-on-mismatch reference, not a checklist** (most items won't apply to any given model); the file says so
itself. Read it there — do not restate it here.

This rule exists only to pull that catalog into context at the moment the bugs get *written* — in a transformer
`forward` or a pipeline `__call__` denoising loop — instead of after a parity mismatch surfaces in review (where
`.ai/review-rules.md` already links it). The traps cluster in a few places worth keeping in mind while editing:

- **dtype of latents / noise / RoPE positions / timesteps** — a ~1e-2 mismatch (float32 vs bfloat16) looks
  harmless but compounds through the denoising loop via 1/sigma amplification into broken output (catalog #2, #5, #9, #10, #11).
- **RNG & seeding** — global CPU RNG vs `torch.Generator`; `patch_size` threaded into noise generation (#1, #4).
- **state across stages** — scheduler accumulators and guider state that must be reset/restored (#6, #8).
- **config & semantics** — published-checkpoint config overriding code defaults; off-by-one guidance-step mapping (#3, #12).

When outputs don't match the reference, open the catalog and compare against it line by line — don't guess.
